They constitute about 10% of the Chinese population in Japan. Until the 1940s, the t...'

[[WP:AES|←]]Created page with 'Chaoxianzu in Korea, (Korean: 재한조선족/在韩朝鲜族),  the Chinese Korean ethnic group with Chinese nationality in South Korea refers to individuals of the Korean ethnic group from China who are residing (without changing nationality), settled (with a South Korean expatriate visa), or immigrated (having changed nationality) to South Korea.   The term [[Jaehan Joseonjok]] (재한조선족) and [[Zaihan Chaoxianzu]] (在韩朝鲜族) refers to Chine...'

According to the Republic of Korea's government, as of October 2023, the population of Chaoxianzu and Korean Chinese holding citizenship of the People's Republic of China (including 1.7 million individuals of Korean ethnicity Chaoxianzu) stands at 1,893,763. Given the consideration of those individuals of Korean ethnicity who have acquired South Korean citizenship, a figure of 2 million appears implausible. Thank you.

The term "중국조선족" is not a single word, but rather it appears as two separate words, "중국" (China) and "조선족" (ethnic Korean group), with a space between them. "Chaoxianzu" is the official term, while "Korean Chinese" is not the official designation.
